  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions aimed at preventing money laundering. Some key examples include:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations, which set international standards for combating money laundering\n\n2. The United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n\n3. The Palermo Convention, which requires countries to criminalize money laundering\n\n4. The Basel Committee's guidelines on banking regulations\n\n5. The European Union's Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n\nThese frameworks require countries to implement domestic laws that:\n- Criminalize money laundering\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Establish customer identification procedures\n- Cooperate in international investigations\n\nMost developed countries have robust anti-money laundering (AML) laws and regulations to detect and prevent financial crimes.",
